<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>go on the bend • go round the bend</xh5><p> <i>go on the bend</i>—(coll.) have a drinking spree: The apprentice may be a wild youth with an earnest desire to <u>go </u>occasionally “<u>upon the bend</u>.”</p><p> <i>go round the bend</i>—(coll.) go crazy or behave as if mad <i>(also: go around the bend):</i> If I don’t get some rest, I’ll <u>go round the bend</u>.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>turn the corner</b>—begin to make a recovery from a serious illness or a difficult time: Has California’s economy finally <u>turned the corner</u>?</p> </entry>
